### Describe the bug

When I compile just https://github.com/YoSTEALTH/Liburing/blob/master/src/liburing/type.pyx file, file-size is around `700KiB - 1.2MiB` using `-Oz` and `--debug`. I am not sure whats taking up all these space.

Even compiling empty `.pxd, .pyx` file is around `60KiB`! Is this normal?

### Code to reproduce the behaviour:

C include header 
``` c
#ifndef __iovec_defined
#define __iovec_defined 1

#define __need_size_t
#include <stddef.h>

/* Structure for scatter/gather I/O.  */
struct iovec
  {
    void *iov_base;	/* Pointer to data.  */
    size_t iov_len;	/* Length of data.  */
  };

#endif
```

comment_data.body:
This is a duplicate of https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/4425

If file size matters, then you should also strip your binaries, i.e. remove debug symbols and data from them. Or pass -g0 or -g1 to the C compiler to avoid generating it in the first place.

It might be worth checking the symbol sizes for your specific module:

`nm --print-size --size-sort --radix=d  some_module.*so`.

In your case I'd be surprised if it was all Cython, just because 1MB sounds really abnormally big given how much Cython code you have

For production code that you want to send to users, `-g0` or `-g1` are much more reasonable than the default `-g2`.

Also see https://cython.readthedocs.io/en/latest/src/userguide/faq.html#how-do-i-reduce-the-size-of-the-binary-modules

From your list of symbol sizes, this one stands out (the largest one):

> `0000000000121728 0000000000017384 t __pyx_memoryview_copy_contents`

The memoryview implementation is known to be quite large. It's not a trivial feature.

I'm aware that there's https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/2356, but that only helps for larger projects (or at least larger installations with multiple Cython based packages). I wonder if it's worth splitting up the memoryview implementation depending on the feature set used in the module: Are slice assignments used or not? Is the Python API used or not? When returning memoryviews from Python functions, then we need the full feature set, but if they are used as a module internal tool, then we might be able to cut down the feature size.

I've created https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/6045 for this idea.

I can live with `-g0` for production, seems like a good option and the filesize is reasonable, thanks @scoder.

I knew I would be dealing with many `*.so` files so I created [Dynamic Import](https://github.com/YoSTEALTH/Dynamic-Import) project to dynamically load `*.so` file depending on what users software uses e.g. `define, function, ...`. This should also save on load time & space.

I didn't know memoryview was so bloated and it was making a copy?! The main reason I used `unsigned char[:] buf; &buf[0]` was to make zero copy and to give bytes Python pointer to C function. Thought it was preventing from making ref-count in `nogil` function and to keep reference to bytes object alive till the pointer is submitted to C back-end event loop function.

> I didn't know memoryview was so bloated and it was making a copy?! The main reason I used unsigned char[:] buf; &buf[0] was to make zero copy and to give bytes Python pointer to C function. Thought it was preventing from making ref-count in nogil function and to keep reference to bytes object alive till the pointer is submitted to C back-end event loop function.

It is not making a copy here.

The problem is that including a memoryview generates the code for many different memoryview operations including some that you don't use (like making a copy).
@da-woods Aww I see, glad its not making a copy :+1: zero copy makes a huge difference. I suppose I have to pay for that feature with extra bloat not used. Thanks for letting me know...

It's true that simply cimporting from a module that uses memoryviews should not make your own module depend on memoryviews if it otherwise doesn't. I created https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/6051 for this.

title: [BUG] `.so` file size too large?
